[2] North Carolina (Bladen County)
Date: Tue 24 Sep 2013
Source: The News Reporter [edited]
http://www.whiteville.com/news/mosquito-borne-illness-kills-th-horse/article_cff649b0-2463-11e3-8282-0019bb2963f4.html


The hot, wet weather of early summer has produced a bumper crop of mosquitoes and deadly microbes.

The North Carolina Department of Agriculture [NCDA] reported last week [week of 16 Sep 013] that an even dozen horses have died of eastern equine encephalitis (EEE) this season [2013]. 10 had died by this time last year [2012].

The disease is carried by mosquitoes that bite infected horses, mules, donkeys, ponies, and miniatures. It can mutate into a deadly form of the disease that affects humans.

Dr Tom Ray of the NCDA said if the number of confirmed, reported cases has hit 12, "there are likely 4 or 5 times that many that aren't reported. "It's been a big year for EEE," he said.

The most recent case of EEE was in a quarter horse gelding that died in Bladen County. Ray said there was a flurry of cases earlier in the season, with 7 animals dying, then a lull, and now a steady climb has begun that could carry through until the 1st killing frost.

[Byline: Jefferson Weaver]

